            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>Here lies Agathe, of 40 years, (passed away) 7 days before the Kalends of September.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Qui giace Agathe, di 40 anni, (morta) 7 giorni prima delle Kalende di Settembre.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The structure of the epitaph is frequent in the Christian age. The name of the deceased recurs in some Paleochristian epitaphs from Catania, such as IG 14.524 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001344">ISic001344</ref>, IG 14.525 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000964">ISic000964</ref>, IG 14.552 = <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic001371">ISic001371</ref>. Kirchhoff’s supplement at l. 3 <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἐτε]λ[εύτησεν τῇ</foreign> does not seem to be necessary (moreover, there is not a lacuna at this line): even if the verb <foreign xml:lang="grc">τελευτάω</foreign> is frequent in this formula after the indication of the years and before the indication of the day of death, a similar structure without the verb <foreign xml:lang="grc">τελευτάω</foreign> recurs also in IGCVO 1380 (Rome). The indication of the day of death as <foreign xml:lang="la">dies natalis</foreign> is common in Christian epitaphs.</p>
            </div>
